The LOP measures 13 ½” from the front of the trigger to the back of the steel buttplate. The stock rates in about Fine overall condition.

Type of Finish: Blue

Finish Originality: All Original

Bore Condition: The bore is bright and the rifling is sharp. There is no erosion.

Overall Condition: This rifle retains about 95% of its metal finish. The balance of the finish shows almost no wear to the barrel. The hard edges on the right side of the receiver show wear and light compressions. The screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. Overall, this rifle rates in about Fine condition.

Mechanics: The action functions Correctly. We have not fired this rifle.

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: One 6-round magazine in Fine condition is included.

Our Assessment: This Weatherby is a fine quality and desirable rifle with its fancy wood Monte Carlo stock. This rifle features a unique single shot semi-auto selector. Teach the kids with the single shot then go plink a boxful with semi-auto.

title: For Sale:  SHARPS MODEL 1853 JOHN BROWN CARBINE
postcontent: This is model 1853 Sharps carbine known to collectors as the "John Brown Slanting Breech” Sharps. It is extremely rare and very collectible. This is the pattern of gun that was acquired by the famous abolitionist John Brown and used on his raid on Harpers Ferry October 16-18, 1859. The barrel is stamped Sharps Rifle Manufacturing Co., Hartford, Connecticut. Lockplate is stamped Sharps Patent 1852. Upper tang is stamped Sharps Patent 1848 along with the serial number 18,823.Total production numbered around 10,500. The lands and grooves in the bore are clearly visible with minor pitting. The rear sight intact, saddle bar and ring, along with the brass hardware. This carbine is very scarce and you won't find many listed especially at this price and condition.
